First we could write $16$ as a power of $2$ (which happens to be $2^4$, just as $16$ itself happens to be $4^2$). In this case it works out, but even if the number didn't wind up simplifying so nicely, we could eventually simplify it using the steps outlined below. \begin{align*}
4^{\log_7x}&=2^4\\ \Rightarrow\qquad\left(2^2\right)^{\log_7x}&=2^4\\ \Rightarrow\qquad2^{2\log_7x}&=2^4 \\ \Rightarrow\qquad 2\log_7x&=4\\ \Rightarrow\qquad \log_7x&=2
\end{align*}We can then convert this last statement into exponential form. \begin{align*}
x &= 7^2\\ &= \boxed{49}
\end{align*}
